╭─ Assistant [MainThread@2067253] ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ I've tried several variations, and the core issue remains the same: the SLP vectorizer     │
│ crashes when it encounters a `poison` value in a context where it expects an               │
│ `Instruction`. The fix needs to handle this `poison` value correctly without preventing    │
│ expected optimizations.                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The regression test `div-possibly-extended-with-poisons.ll` fails because the vectorizer   │
│ is no longer performing an expected `udiv` vectorization. This happens because my previous │
│ fixes incorrectly signaled that the conditions for a specific optimization (truncation of  │
│ `udiv`) were not met.                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct logic is: when a `poison` value is encountered, we should assume it *does*     │
│ satisfy the condition. A `poison` value is undefined, so we are free to assume it has      │
│ whatever properties are convenient for optimization. In this case, we assume its upper     │
│ bits are zero, which allows the `udiv` to be truncated and subsequently vectorized.        │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply the correct patch.                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```diff                                                                                    │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                      │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                      │
│ @@ -17997,8 +17997,13 @@                                                                   │
│      auto Checker = [&](unsigned BitWidth, unsigned OrigBitWidth) {                        │
│        assert(BitWidth <= OrigBitWidth && "Unexpected bitwidths!");                        │
│        return all_of(E.Scalars, [&](Value *V) {                                            │
│ -        auto *I = cast<Instruction>(V);                                                   │
│ -        APInt Mask = APInt::getBitsSetFrom(OrigBitWidth, BitWidth);                       │
│ +        if (!isa<Instruction>(V)) {                                                       │
│ +          // This must be a poison value. It can be anything, so we can                   │
│ +          // assume it is a value where the truncated bits are zero.                      │
│ +          return true;                                                                    │
│ +        }                                                                                 │
│ +        auto *I = cast<Instruction>(V);                                                   │
│ +        const APInt Mask = APInt::getBitsSetFrom(OrigBitWidth, BitWidth);                 │
│          return MaskedValueIsZero(I->getOperand(0), Mask, SimplifyQuery(*DL)) &&           │
│                 MaskedValueIsZero(I->getOperand(1), Mask, SimplifyQuery(*DL));             │
│        });                                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
